title: NASA to Provide Update Today on Last Major Artemis Test Before Launch
summary: NASA to Provide Update Today on Last Major Test Before Artemis Launch

title: NASA scrubs first attempt at SLS countdown rehearsal
summary: NASA called off the first attempt to fuel its Space Launch System rocket and go through a practice countdown April 3, citing a problem with the rocket’s mobile launcher.

title: Rogozin delays decision on space station future
summary: After Western nations refused his demand to end sanctions on Russian companies involved in the International Space Station, the head of Roscosmos said he will make recommendations in the “near future” on Russia’s continued participation in the station, but there are no signs of any near-term changes in station operations.

title: Private mission ready for launch to the ISS
summary: The first private mission to the International Space Station by an American vehicle is scheduled to launch this week to serve as a first step in one company’s plans to establish a commercial space station.

title: SLS wet dress rehearsal scrubbed ahead of final major pre-flight test for NASA moon rocket
summary: With the arrival of SLS and Orion at Pad-B on March 18, engineers and technicians were busy making final preparations for Sunday’s critical last design verification test: the Wet Dress Rehearsal, or WDR.  However, the test was scrubbed for at least 24 hours ahead of fueling ops due to problems in providing positive pressure to the enclosed areas within Mobile Launcher -1 (ML-1) to keep out hazardous gases.

title: Spacewalks, crewed missions, and science: March in orbit aboard the ISS
summary: The International Space Station (ISS) and its astronauts had a busy March as teams performed spacewalks, welcomed new crewmembers, said goodbye to those returning to Earth, and prepared for the arrival of the first private mission to the iconic orbital outpost. All the while, groundbreaking science research was being performed using the space station’s many labs and instruments.

title: Commercial BlackSky imaging satellites ride with Rocket Lab
summary: Two microsatellites for BlackSky launched Saturday from New Zealand, riding a Rocket Lab launch vehicle into orbit to join a fleet of commercial eyes supplying imagery to military and civilian users.

title: 37th Space Symposium attendance to top 10,000
summary: More than 10,000 people are expected to attend the 37th Space Symposium in person at the Broadmoor Hotel in Colorado Springs and online through a virtual platform.

title: Rocket Lab launches BlackSky satellites as it prepares for mid-air booster recovery
summary: A Rocket Lab Electron launched another pair of imaging satellites for BlackSky April 2 as the company gears up to attempt recovery of the rocket’s first stage.

title: Russia asked NASA to end sanctions to save the ISS, but the West didn’t blink
summary: "Sustaining safe and successful ISS operations remains a priority for the United States."
